{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.07,0.07,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116545"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7249"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116545"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skull comprises several bones united by fibrous joints called sutures. These structures provide essential anatomical landmarks for clinical assessment and developmental evaluation. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"The coronal suture is located between which bones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Frontal and parietal","Frontal and temporal","Parietal and occipital","Temporal and parietal","The two parietal bones"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and parietal bones\u003C/strong\u003E are united by the coronal suture, which traverses the skull laterally in a crown-like configuration from one temporal region to the other.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo parietal bones\u003C/strong\u003E articulate via the sagittal suture that courses along the cranial midline. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal and parietal bones\u003C/strong\u003E join at the squamous suture positioned on the lateral skull aspect. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal and occipital bones\u003C/strong\u003E connect through the lambdoid suture, forming a distinctive inverted V configuration at the skull\u0027s posterior aspect. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and temporal bones\u003C/strong\u003E lack a direct sutural articulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding sutural anatomy is essential for assessing normal paediatric cranial development and identifying pathological conditions such as craniosynostosis, where premature sutural fusion occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The coronal suture forms the junction between the frontal bone anteriorly and the parietal bones posteriorly.","The sagittal suture runs along the midline connecting the two parietal bones, while the lambdoid suture joins the parietal and occipital bones."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Skull sutures\u0022 by OpenStax College is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:901_Skull_Sutures.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98538"}},"question":{"data":{"typ